08242nam a22010815i 9780226619941DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019024315  a9780226619941  a(DE-B1597)535679  a(OCoLC)1135577925  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aS494.5.P75bA373 2019 4aS494.5.P75bA373 2020 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a338.1622300aAgricultural Productivity and Producer Behavior /ced. by Wolfram Schlenker. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b130 figures, 57 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Heterogeneous Yield Impacts from Adoption of Genetically Engineered Corn and the Importance of Controlling for Weather -- t2. Impacts of Climate Change and Extreme Weather on US Agricultural Productivity: Evidence and Projection -- t3. Farming under Weather Risk: Adaptation, Moral Hazard, and Selection on Moral Hazard -- t4. Intranational Trade Costs, Reallocation, and Technical Change: Evidence from a Canadian Agricultural Trade Policy Reform -- t5. Electricity Prices, Groundwater, and Agriculture: The Environmental and Agricultural Impacts of Electricity Subsidies in India -- t6. Estimating the Impact of Crop Diversity on Agricultural Productivity in South Africa -- t7. Crop Disease and Agricultural Productivity: Evidence from a Dynamic Structural Model of Verticillium Wilt Management -- t8. Willingness to Pay for Low Water Footprint Foods during Drought -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAgricultural yields have increased steadily in the last half century, particularly since the Green Revolution. At the same time, inflation-adjusted agricultural commodity prices have been trending downward as increases in supply outpace the growth of demand. Recent severe weather events, biofuel mandates, and a switch toward a more meat-heavy diet in emerging economies have nevertheless boosted commodity prices. Whether this is a temporary jump or the beginning of a longer-term trend is an open question. Agricultural Productivity and Producer Behavior examines the factors contributing to the remarkably steady increase in global yields and assesses whether yield growth can continue. This research also considers whether such growth will impose significant environmental externalities. Among the topics studied are genetically modified crops; changing climatic factors; farm production responses to government regulations including crop insurance, transport subsidies, and electricity subsidies for groundwater extraction; and the role of specific farm practices such as crop diversification, disease management, and water-saving methods. This research provides new evidence that technological as well as policy choices influence agricultural productivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAgricultural productivityvCongresses. 0aAgricultural productivityzUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aAgricultural productivity. 0aAgricultural subsidiesvCongresses. 0aAgricultural subsidieszUnited StatesvCongresses. 0aAgricultural subsidies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aagricultural production.  aclimate change impacts.  acrop diversity.  acrop insurance.  apest infection.  asustainable agriculture.  atechnology innovation.  atrade cost.1 aBadiani-Magnusson, Reena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBall, Eldon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellora, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https